      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The general principle under Queensland common law is that the owner of the property that benefits from the retaining wall, typically the uphill property owner whose land is being supported, is responsible for the cost of maintaining and repairing that wall. Where a wall sits on a boundary line between two properties, or where both properties benefit from the wall, responsibility can be shared. Disputes about boundary retaining walls are governed by common law rather than the Dividing Fences Act 1953 (Qld), which applies to fences but not retaining structures. If there is genuine uncertainty about responsibility for a specific wall, a solicitor can advise on the position."
      }
    },
